# Hook Configuration JSON Schema

Based on the documentation provided, here's the JSON schema for hook configuration in `settings.json`:

## Basic Structure

```json
{
  "hooks": {
    "EVENT_NAME": [
      {
        "type": "command",
        "command": "path/to/script.sh"
      },
      {
        "type": "http",
        "url": "https://example.com/webhook",
        "method": "POST",
        "headers": {
          "Authorization": "Bearer ${TOKEN}"
        },
        "allowedEnvVars": ["TOKEN"]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

## Hook Restrictions

```json
{
  "allowManagedHooksOnly": true,
  "allowedHttpHookUrls": [
    "https://hooks.example.com/*",
    "http://localhost:*"
  ],
  "httpHookAllowedEnvVars": [
    "MY_TOKEN",
    "HOOK_SECRET"
  ]
}
```

## Key Configuration Options

| Setting | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `allowManagedHooksOnly` | (Managed settings only) Only load managed and SDK hooks; block user, project, and plugin hooks |
| `allowedHttpHookUrls` | Allowlist of URL patterns HTTP hooks may target. Supports `*` wildcard. Arrays merge across scopes |
| `httpHookAllowedEnvVars` | Allowlist of environment variable names HTTP hooks may interpolate into headers. Each hook's effective list is the intersection with this setting |

## Notes

- **Environment Variables**: HTTP hooks can interpolate environment variables into headers using `${VAR_NAME}` syntax
- **URL Patterns**: Support `*` as wildcard for matching
- **Array Merging**: When the same setting appears in multiple scopes, arrays are concatenated and deduplicated
- **Validation**: Hooks with non-matching URLs are silently blocked

For complete hook documentation including event types and advanced configuration, see the [hooks documentation](/en/hooks).

